## First Strike as System Activation

Lightning Vessel does not generate lightning from empty air.

However, if an external lightning event enters the system, the first strike acts as an activation impulse.

Before the strike, the vessel exists in a prepared state:

text seawater pumps are ready tower reservoirs are filled ultrasonic emitters are active event sensors are monitoring mist and geyser systems are prepared water mufflers are charged with water 

After the strike, the system enters an active state.

The captured event produces steam, pressure, ionized mist, acoustic shock, and secondary waves.

At the same time, the vessel can push more seawater upward through geyser towers, increasing the amount of water, vapor, aerosol, and droplets in the air.

text first strike → steam / pressure / ionized mist → pumps increase water flow → towers raise more seawater → ultrasound structures droplets and vapor → artificial cloud layer expands → secondary waves receive a larger medium 

In this way, the first strike helps create the very medium that may slow the disappearance of the lightning event.

The system does not hold the original lightning channel forever.

Instead, it uses the first strike to build a larger water-vapor-plasma environment where secondary waves, delayed flashes, artificial cloud formation, and ball-lightning-like plasma-vapor states may persist longer than the original discharge.

---

### Activation Chain

text External lightning = starter First strike = activation impulse Seawater = working mass Pumps = vertical lift Ultrasound = structure Artificial cloud = holding medium Secondary waves = continuation Slow decay = visible ending 

